animal.description:
**Courtesy Listing-please contact the shelter directly **

Seattle Humane  
13212 SE Eastgate Way, Bellevue, WA 98005   seattlehumane.org
(425) 641-0080

**UPDATE 1/21/21 from Foster Home**

Foster Dog Name: Cha Cha

What do you like most about your foster dog?

She is such a fun little puppy. She is playful and learns things quickly, she's also a super
cuddler. She will actively seek out affection and belly rubs and generally likes to cozy up
with you. She's also a bit of a goofball. She will randomly start licking the fireplace with her eyes closed or wiggle around on the ground trying to catch her own tail while wagging it
hard enough to continuously whack herself in the face with it. It's funny, she'll be off doing
her own thing and you'll just look over and start laughing at whatever antic she's in the
middle of.

While in foster, this pet has interacted with (people): Adults Only

While in foster, this pet has interacted with (other pets):
 
How has your foster dog responded to: new people, children, or other pets?

She's wary of new people but as she's gotten more comfortable with us, she's also become
more trusting of strangers when we tell her they're ok. She actively looks to us to see if they
are a threat and if she should be afraid, after an introduction and assurance that they won't
hurt her she will approach them on her own and ask for pets and kisses. She's developed a
considerable amount of trust in the last month of being here

Were there any pets or people in the home with whom your foster dog did not
interact?

Describe your foster dogs typical routine while in your home:

Wake up, go outside and run around a bit before breakfast, hang out in the office or on the
couch until lunch while keeping an eye out for squirrels in the yard, a walk at lunchtime,
hang out again until 5 and then will come stare at us and tell us that boring work time is
over now, longer walk after work, dinner at 6ish, then playtime inside or outside with toys
(no biting!), then curl up on the couch with you until bedtime. She normally gets a second
wind of playfulness around 9:30, we play with her inside toys then she'll crash and be ready for bed. She sleeps on the bed with her stuffed thing. If she forgets the stuffed thing, she'll
run out and get it and come back to bed with it.

How would you describe your foster dog's energy level?

Generally fairly calm with a few peaks of bonkers bananas throughout the day. She'll run
around outside like a maniac for about 10-15 minutes and then she'll abruptly go inside,
drink water and pass out. Prey drive is high and will get her into an agitated state.

What kinds of physical and mental exercise have your foster dog received in
your care?

walks, yard play, stuffed kongs, food puzzles, trick training, toy variety, Other: Hide and seek

Did your foster dog show a preference for any of those forms of enrichment?

She likes all of them. She'll bite if she gets too riled up with toys so hide and seek or trick training is good to mix in to yard play

What has your foster dog eaten for meals and treats? Have you found any food
or treats to be of high value to them? (The standard food offered for SH dogs is
Nutrisource: chicken and rice formula.)

Kibble with a spoonful of wet over it. Shows an insensitivity to beef wet food, keep her on
chicken.

If your foster dog has been on medication, what has been the most successful
strategy for medicating, including administering?

She's easy, just put it in with her food

Have you noticed anything that caused signs of fear, anxiety, or stress (FAS) in
your foster dog? If yes, please describe what may have caused that response.

She's nervous around people, you have to be intentional about introductions. She doesn't
like when one of us leaves the house. If you distract her and she doesn't notice the person
leave, it's not a big deal. She only whines, she's not destructive and she'll settle down after a
while. The bathroom freaks her out, she does NOT want a bath. We don't take her in there,
we bathe her with a hot/cold water connection we have outside for just this purpose and
she does fine. If she's following you around the house though, she'll hard stop before going
into any bathroom.

What training cues (hand signals and/or words) does your foster dog reliably
perform, if any? Ex: sit, shake, down

Sit, Shake, Down, Stay, we're working on a more reliable "come"she's 75% in the house, outside with smells and potential prey she's probably at 4% recall.

Where has your foster dog stayed when left alone? How long have they been
left alone?

We've only left her alone for maybe an hour or two? Ha ha, we don't leave the house much
now. She stayed at home and was fine, no destruction though I'm sure she cried for a bit
after we left.

Would you consider your foster dog to be fully house-trained? Yes

How has your foster dog indicated when they need to go out?

She doesn't really... she's never needed to tell us to take her out, we take her out frequently
enough for her needs.

She's good in the car. She will look out the window, or just curl up in a ball and go to sleep.

What else have you learned that can help your foster dog succeed? (i.e.
environmental set-up, interactions, routines, overcoming challenges)

Her prey drive is strong, we've put visual barriers over some of our windows as even a
squirrel running up a tree 20ft away will have her 100% focus. If an animal gets too close to
the window, she will lunge and attack the window. If she gets off leash and sees prey, it's
game over. She's 100% into the prey, not you (mouse or horse) so be aware of your
surroundings. She bites when she gets over stimulated so do short bursts of play and then
mix in training play especially around impulse control. Sit/Stay/Wait for treat, etc. If she
starts going for ankles or jumps to bite your hand say a firm No Biting or even just Don't
and she's getting better and remembering to calm it down, reward her with kisses when she
remembers to not bite. She's getting to the point that she'll come at you with teeth and
course correct with kissing, seeing progress there.



Cha Cha is a 2.5yr old, spayed Cattle dog/Border Collie mix that weighs 44 pounds. She is super cute, perfect size and has the silliest sleeping positions! She came to us as a transfer from a shelter down in Southern WA back in March 2020. She was brought in as a stray and was very shut down and scared at that shelter. She was pretty shut down with us at first too and after a few days of staff working with her, she began to warm up! She has been in a variety of different foster homes where we’ve learned a lot about her during this time. Cha Cha is fear reactive to new people and other dogs. She also has an incredibly high prey drive for small animals such as rabbits, squirrels, birds, cats, etc. She is VERY smart and learns super quick, but needs someone that understands her breed along with able to continue working on her socialization to people. She dog tested fine at her previous shelter with other dogs, but was timid, avoidant and shut down around them. She has done ok with some dogs that she’s met here, but as she’s gotten more comfortable in her foster homes, the more reactive she has become to other dogs on leash, thus we’ve made her needing to be the only dog in the home. We also aren’t conducting dog tests at this time due to covid restrictions, so by default she needs to be the only pet in the home. Cha Cha can also escape out of doorways and some types of fencing, so she will need a secure yard with a fence. In her most recent home, she escaped out a side door and ran across to the neighbor’s home and chased/herded the horses in the pasture for a long time. She loves toys and has an incredible interest/drive in certain types of toys, so training with toys as a motivator is also an option for her! She is very sweet, loving and cuddly when she’s comfy and warms up to you! She loves to be on laps, couches, playing with toys, out exploring and chilling in backyards. She’d make a wonderful dog for someone who lives a bit more rural, has a fenced yard and no other pets. We think she’d best with teens or older kids in the home. Medically, Cha Cha is healthy, but she is an anxious dog, thus she is on some anti-anxiety meds.

Seattle Humane   
13212 SE Eastgate Way, Bellevue, WA 98005   seattlehumane.org

**Foster update 1/21/21**
Audrey is an affectionate and playful pitbull who is looking for someone who wants to spend time with her and give her lots of attention. She loves to play tug of war and run around the backyard. She just wants to be wherever you are and do whatever you are doing. She loves to cuddle at night and sleep right next to you to keep warm.

What does this dog's diet consist of? prescription diet w/d wet and dry food

This dog's temperament tends to be: Friendly, Playful, Gentle, Affectionate

What is this dog's general activity level? Mellow, Fairly Calm

Do you have any additional comments regarding this dog's energy level?
She likes to play tug of war and do a run thru the yard. At times she wants to be very affectionate and will put her arms around your neck to hug and then work her way onto your lap. She then goes a little crazy trying to lick your ear or face.

What do you like most about this dog?
I love how she likes to cuddle in bed and how she likes to hug. It's very sweet.

Does this dog have any favorite toys or games? If so, what are they?
Loves the rope and the kong jumbler ball that squeaks. She does get excited eating her treats out of the snuffle mat.

In foster care, this dog lived with: Men, Women, Children

If children selected, please list the ages: 17 year old

If dogs selected, please specify the size and breed:
N/A

Describe your foster dog's typical day:
On weekdays she sleeps in until about 7am then she eats and goes outside to go to the bathroom and sniff around the yard. She then will come in and lay on the bed in my office and nap. Throughout the day I will let her out back and she likes to chase any squirrels and just smell everything. Then she comes back in. I do this with her ALL day. Then
on weekends she'll sleep until about 8-8:30 then I feed her and put her out. And we do the indoor/outdoor all day again. She will play with her toys off and on as well.

Describe the daily exercise this dog received in foster care:
Running in the backyard. I have taken her for a couple of walks and she is VERY strong.

How does this dog react to other dogs?
Avoided other animals so not sure

How does this dog react to cats?
Didn't see any

How does this dog react to new people?
She gets really excited and jumps on them so if not prepared will knock you over. Usually she will calm down after 5-10 minutes.

How does this dog react to children?
Only had her around my cousin who is 18 months and she was fine. She wanted to lick his face which was a problem but she wasn't aggressive or mean to him. Just had to pay attention so she didn't knock him over since he was smaller than her then she walked by him. She also would try and take his food if she was near him but not in an aggressive way. Just if he dropped some or walked away.

What training cues does this dog know? (ex. sit, shake, come)
She can sit, shake, come and lay down. If you say do you want a treat she seems to know that as well.

Is this dog fully house-trained? How often do they have mistakes? Do they indicate when they need to go out?
She is fully house trained and had no accidents. She can hold it for a long time. She goes out a lot during the day so she has never needed to indicate she needed to go out.

Where does this dog stay when left alone? How long can they be left alone? Can they be trusted in a house alone?
I have left her up to 3 hours alone and let her have the whole house. She has not done any damage while alone and when I come home she is sitting on the couch sleeping. She doesn't seem to be stressed out being alone but she always wants to go with you.

How does this foster dog do in the car?
She is good in the car. At first she wants to come in the front but will just sit in the back or lay down pretty quickly.

Does this foster dog have any naughty habits that need to be worked on? Is there anything you noticed that this dog is afraid of?
She does like to hump and lick or nibble your ears. But it's not so bad that you can't get her off of you when you push her away.

List your top 3 favorite things about this dog:
Affectionate, Loving, Sweet

Audrey is a 3yr 2mos old, spayed Staffy mix! She’s a thick girl and weighs 74 pounds! She is SO loving, wiggly, active, and sweet! She  just recently came back to us after being adopted for almost 11mos. Her owners loved her very much and were sad to give her up. They had a recent lifestyle changed that resulted in her needing to come back to us. Prior to that, we had Audrey for quite a while due to her having extreme shelter stress on campus and not presenting herself well. Thankfully, she was adopted for nearly a year and is a completely different dog now! She has mellowed out quite a bit and has much better leash manners, greeting manners, and just all around more docile. She used to be quite rambunctious and was difficult to handle on leash due to her strength and would just get over excited about everything. Since she’s been back with us, we’ve seen very different behaviors this time. She is still her happy, excited self, but doesn’t get nearly as rambunctious nor have we seen any mouthing or her getting super amped up. When she was with us a year ago, she was highly reactive to other dogs, however, she has had a variety of dog friends on campus. She’s got a history of scuffles though and Audrey doesn’t respond the best to corrections, thus we made her needing to be the only pet in the home. While in her adoptive home, she was also said to be reactive and hyper around other dogs on leash. While with us now, she’s seen dogs on leash and hasn’t been reactive. She has shown excitement, but not aggression. We still have her as needing to be the only pet in the home and preferring a fenced yard, but she could have dog friends in the future with careful intros. She is so sweet, playful, loving and cuddly! She thinks she’s a lap dog sometimes and loves the water too! Audrey would do best with teens or older kids in the home too. Medically, Audrey is overweight and has hypothyroidism. We have been unable to secure a foster home for her, so she is on campus, but is doing well right now. We’d love to get her in foster or an adoptive home! She is on meds for that along with some anti-anxiety meds too.

animal.description:
Want a fitness inspo? Here's Bebe!

Hey guys! Checkin' out my shred bod? My name is Bebe and I am about 9 months old, female German Shepherd-Husky wonder mix. I have seen a whole lot in my short life and that's how I grew stronger. I was left at a vet at Valle de Guadalupe, at just 3 months old, where I was stuffed in a crate and that was it. For 3 months! My back legs took a huge hit and my muscles gave away completely. When TAP and a local rescue got me out to San Diego, double amputation was determined to be the best option for me. Did that get me down? Hell nawww! Lack of two legs cant extinguish the fire within me! My surgeries are done and I am undergoing physical therapy and swimming that have led to my ripped front legs. Heck, I can race ya when I am on my wheels! A 3 miler is nothing for this girl.

I am a super friendly girl and have become somewhat of a neighborhood fav! When I see my chariot being brought out, I know that it's time for some fun. I start my walks-on-wheels, and I literally stop the traffic because, well, it's me. There is a great chance that I will be one of those Insta-famous athletes, rolling off on her front legs only. With my water-therapy in full progress, it's just a matter of time! Regarding bathroom training, I have incontinence, so I may need help with clean-up. I don't need to be expressed, but wiping up is needed for this lady. When I am chilling in the house, I prefer to have a drag-bag, just to not scratch up my skin. That's only until I am fully mobile on my front legs.

I do have a feisty personality and I am quite strong-willed. Some training and positive reinforcement will go a long way for me, since afterall, I am still a pup! I am curious, smart and I love to be mentally stimulated. And I do have a mind of my own. I will fetch when I want it. :D Behavioral training has been helping me tons. But I do guarantee, that a life with me will be full of the most amazing moments. Nothing less than a firecracker life, with this firecracker! I will need dedicated time for my care, therapy and clean-ups. If you are ready for an extraordinary life with a true blue rescue, come and say hi! My adoption fee is $150 and that includes spaying/neutering, shots, and microchip. If you want to take me home, please fill out the form on the website here https://theanimalpad.org/adoption-application/

animal.description:
Big Mike - 7 years old 

He is such a good boy. 
He’s great with strangers, he loves pets from them. He doesn’t like long car rides, I think he gets motion sick, but likes short ones. He walks well, with manners, but you have to show you’re in charge. He is potty trained. He loves looking out the front window. He is good with older kids, because he doesn’t know he’s big. 

Storms cause him anxiety, unless he’s by you. 
He really prefers to be solo with his human, not fond of sharing toys. He is a definite lap dog. He LIVES FOR walkies as we call them. He will go to his leash all the time, but he’s older now so he doesn’t like to go very far as he gets super tired. The less humid the farther we go. Loves his toys and tearing up squeaky tennis balls.
If he is over an adventure, he will lay down. And be annoyed if you make him get up to go to the car. I thought he was like sick once, but he was literally just protesting.
He does have separation and confinement issues.
Big Mike, above all else, is a lover. 
He’s afraid of “alpha dogs” and doesn’t play well with cats or small animals. Loves kiddos, and cuddles from them, but not his ears pulled or being poked. Definitely a mix between lap dog and Mr. Independent. In classic big dog fashion, doesn’t know he’s big! He thinks that beds and couches are free game. He’s a dog that needs interaction. He craves it with his humans. He doesn’t like being left alone and can get very, very anxious. He has passed two training programs, but he will totally pretend sometimes that he has no idea what any basic command is until you pause and give him the eyebrow.  If he does something he shouldn’t, call him Michael and he puts himself in time out. He’s a great boy, but if adopted, will require patience while he adapts.
animal.name: Big Mike

animal.description:
Levi is a Basenji 

Levi does need a while to warm up to new people and that he exhibits his initial mistrust by trying to nip at you and putting on a show isn’t helping his cause, either. 

Deep down, however, he is nothing but a big softy any the neediest cuddle bug around. 

If he is given the chance Levi will  be an ideal partner-in-crime for an all female household or a patient guy who likes to watch sports on a comfy couch rather than run around the block himself. 

Levi is 7-8 years old, gets along with most other dogs, and also doesn’t mind cats.

He has had a rough start in life and is wary of new people at first. Once he knows you are not out there to hurt him he warms up pretty quickly. 

Levi is ok with other dogs. He is selective. 

Levi loves women and can be a real charmer. He also gets along very well with other dogs. He is very suspicious of men in general and will take some time to trust them. Once he is convinced that you are not going to hurt him he will be extremely loyal. 

Levi has been in a 4-week training camp and know basic commands and walks on the leash very mannerly. His trainer Reann says about him: "Levi's new person must be willing to continue the training he started with us. He knows sit, down, stay, heel and come on the leash."

Our adoption fee for Orchid is $200 and includes her spay, current shots, rabies vaccine, and a registered microchip. If you would like to adopt this Amazing dog, please fill out our online adoption application at www.amazinggracebullyrescue.org

If you have any questions, please text your question to 723-2037. You may also send a message to our Amazing Grace Bully Rescue Page on Facebook, Twitter, Instagram, or send an email directly to amazinggracebullyrescue@gmail.com

This sweet girl is around a year old and about 50 pounds and her breed is a best guess.   She was picked up as a stray and found herself in the Conroe Animal Shelter in Texas where she became very overwhelmed.  The shelter staff saw how stressed out she was and reached out to one of the volunteers with Lola’s Lucky Day to ask if she could take Claire to her home.  She of course said yes!  Once she was in a foster home, her personality blossomed! 

Claire is able to coexist with other  dogs but slow and proper introductions are needed.  She would love an active family and a fenced in yard, although this is not a requirement.  Claire has a goofy personality, is very intelligent, loves to please, is HIGHLY food motivated and enjoys eating (who doesn’t?!).  She has been working on her leash training, but she could use a little fine tuning of her leash manners.  We would recommend her go to a home with older children who understand boundaries and manners when around dogs.  Claire is crate trained and almost potty trained but can sometimes get an anxious piddle if startled.  If you think Claire could be the girl for you, let us know!

animal.description:
Moxie is a strong, loving, cautious, alert, silly, playful and full of character girl. She was adopted out as a pup and returned when other members of the family brought home dogs that she couldn't get along with, thus causing her to lose her home. We believe Moxie needs a home that loves the American bully cross with a Staffordshire or Pitbull. This breed combination is extremely loyal, affectionate and protective, so experience is absolutely needed for an adopter. Experience with either breed or both is a plus!

Moxie learns quickly, walks well on a leash, takes to training like a fish to water, swims in water like a true fish, plays with toys and doesn't mind sharing with her person, and will truly be a partner til the end. She has shown an inclination to attach to her handlers, so multiple person households have to work with her equally. We advise no little children as she is a big girl and needs an adult leader as well as a home that can focus on her needs. We also are looking for an active household that enjoys being outside, walking/hiking and exploring, this young lady needs her mind to be nourished by mother nature's medicinal presence.

Moxie is currently in a training program where she learns basic obedience, leash skills and socializing alongside new people and dogs. We expect an owner to be open to training and commit to learning about Moxie alongside us.

If interested call us at 847-338-3252 or email at Info@redemptionroadinc.org

animal.description:
Hi!  My name is Grainger.  I'm a young labrador retriever and cattledog mix about 1-1/2 yrs old who was turned into Rescue when my owner did not come find me after i got lost.  I am a nice friendly boy so when no one responded to the "found dog" postings, i came to Rescue to make sure i would stay safe.  I am a friendly dog, good with other dogs and people.  I am very agile and like to climb so i do need a very secure environment with a 6' fence and supervision when I am outside. and lots of attention.  I am young and busy so I would be best in a home where i have a k9 buddy and/or someone is home to keep me company.  I would be best in a home with owners experienced with high energy dogs.  Rescue has had me neutered and vaccinated so i'm ready to go home when the right home and family comes along.  I'm enjoying my stay here with Rescue, lots of fun time with other dogs, but i am missing having a family of my own to love ... Couldn't you make room in your home and your heart for a friendly spotted boy like me?

If you are interested in meeting me, please email Dalmatian Rescue of Southern California at dalrescue@sbcglobal.net, tell them you are interested in meeting me and you will be send an adoption questionnaire to be completed and emailed back.  You should also be able to access the questionnaire on line from our website homepage, www.dalrescuesocal.com.  Once the completed questionnaire has been received and if it looks like I might be a good fit for you and your family, arrangements can be quickly made for you and your family and other dog if you have one, to come meet me.  I like making new friends so please, contact Dalmatian Rescue of Southern California, Inc. by email as soon as you can, and ask about me, Grainger.  Thanks.

To learn more about Dalmatian Rescue of Southern California, Inc., a 501c3 non-profit charity, and to see all of our available dogs, please visit our website at www.dalrescuesocal.com.  You can also visit us on facebook at www.facebook.com/spottyfriends.  We love seeing posts and photos of life with your spotty friends so please, keep them coming.  Thanks!

Fostered in Martinsburg WV
Arwen is preferred to be an only dog, she is still being socialized around other dogs and dislikes cats (she chases them if in sight) 
She hasn’t been around children but if she sees them running while in the yard she wants to also chase. This may not necessarily be a bad thing, she may want to play but would most likely play too rough so we prefer a home with older children or no children if possible. She loves snuggles and attention from people.

If you have further questions regarding medical needs please reach out to us. In general she just needs a quiet home. We can only do a foster to adopt situation for her as she needs to get retested in a few months. Message us if you’d like to apply.

animal.description:
Joey is a sweet, funny and playful boy who loves to swim, ride in cars sitting up like a kangaroo and loves his yummy treats!    This darling three-legged boy has the dreamiest brown eyes and will win you over with his sweet disposition and loving gaze.   Joey is approximately 16- 18 months old and has many great years ahead to shower his family with love and provide lots of laughs.

Joey's ready for the best of his life with a family of his own and his perfect match would be someone who loves dogs and and will help him feel safe and at ease in his new home environment.  Joey has done great with sweet, neutral females and done well with proper introductions of male dogs.   Joey has been around children and been very sweet but has always been actively supervised, as all dogs should be.

Joey loves learning and a trainer will facilitate his meet & greet with his lucky family!  

Joey was rescued from Miami Dade Animal Services with an open fracture to his left, front leg and a neurological injury to the right, front leg that resulted in an amputation.     That doesn't get Joey down, and this three legged wonder can dash great distances, especially if he’s chasing down lizards or squirrels - oh yes, this angel has a strong prey drive so no chickens, lizards or other small creatures for this guy's new home!

If you can’t resist this handsome boy’s eyes and are interested in making him your new furry best friend, please complete the adoption application and tell us a little about yourself.  You may be the perfect match for darling Joey!

animal.special_needs_notes:
If you want to fall in love with a very special pup, then you have to meet Joey!

Joey is a sweet, smart, handsome and and loving boy and ready for a family of his own.  

He's a young dog who enjoys leash walks and hanging with his people but he loves nothing more than chilling with a yummy treat at his person's feet.  Joey's been making friends with doggies and does well with proper introductions and with respectful pups.    He sometimes tires easily on walks but enjoys time outside and shows a lot of interest in squirrels and lizards so has a high prey drive for chasing quick moving critters.

Joey suffered a severe fracture to his left, front leg and had surgery to repair the fracture and is fully recovered.    This sweet angel also a neurological  injury to his other front leg that required amputation but he doesn't let having three legs get him down.  

He loves people and enjoys treats, cuddles and hanging with his family.   Ideally, Joey will live in a first floor home so that he can go right outside to potty.    Joey has not been with children and he would do best in a home with oder kids - 12 or so and above, and loves learning.  His new family will get an amazing family pet, fully vaccinated, microchipped and neutered and ready for the rest of his life in  a home of his own.

animal.description:
Hi!  My name is GRONK! My foster family sometimes calls me Wonky Gronky because my right ear doesn’t lay down, I have two different color eyes and I have an underbite - but they say that’s part of what makes me so irresistibly cute!  The other part comes from my sweet, human-adoring personality!
I am 2.5 years old and came back to the rescue after learning that I would thrive better in an environment without small animals (I like to bark at small dogs) or small children...I’m a bit of a nervous fellow. However, because the wonderful people at Adore-A-Bull saw that I needed some structure and training, they brought me back and are putting me through a board-and-train program! Now I’m gaining the confidence to be the bestest, happiest doggo I can be!
I weigh about 50 lbs and have a boxer-type build. I get along great with my siblings - both four-legged and two-legged. When I get free time at training my favorite thing is to lay my head on my trainer’s knee - I just love him so much! My foster mom says someone is going to be really lucky when they take me home for forever...could it be you?!
.
If you are interested in GRONK or any of our dogs, you must live with a 40 mile radius of the Downtown Cincinnati, OH area. Please go to www.adoreabull.org/interested to learn how to start an adoption process.

If you have questions on why we restrict our adoption area, please go back get to http://adoreabull.org/interested/adoption-radius/

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Due to Covid 19, no visits are allowed without an approved application. To apply for this dog, please go to www.adoggie4you.org. Please no phone calls. Adoption fee for this dog is $200. The dog is approximately 6 years old.

My name is Booger. I used to have a daddy that was a special friend to A Doggie 4 You, but one day he sat down in his chair and we couldn't wake him up. We kept trying for several days. We were very hungry and scared. It was really hot and we didn't know what to do. Finally we heard people trying to break in. We knew we had to protect daddy, so we wouldn't let them in. We did our best, but these men in uniforms came in and put a tight noose around our necks and dragged us away. We fought hard and were very scared, especially when we were thrown in a closed truck then a scary pen that was very noisy.

Finally a friend of our foster mom came to pick us up. We heard them trying to convince her to let them put us to sleep. But she said no and they loaded us up and took us to the ranch. We were really scared when we got there, even though we knew our foster mom. But we didn't trust anyone. It didn't take long for us to recognize we weren't in danger anymore. We still miss dad, but our foster mom is really nice and she says she misses dad too. The nice people here taught us how to walk on a leash, get in a kennel, and play with toys. We are really excited about finding a new family. I really like to play with small boys. I used to have a neighbor who would come play with me. I do have a little arthritis, so I can't run too long. I am also a little overweight, so they have me on a diet.

animal.description:
Venus is a gorgeous 3-year-old girl with beautiful tricolor markings who was brought into CACC as a stray. Sadly, her body shows the signs of many litters of puppies and her fear of people leads us to believe she had a rough past. Luckily, those days are behind her now, and while she has some struggles to work through, it’s all up from here for this loveable girl! 

Venus loves the resident dogs she currently lives with but is wary of strange dogs and would likely need slow intros to any new dogs. She chases all small animals she sees so she should not be placed in a home with cats or other small animals.  She also should not be homed with children at this time due to her fear of strangers and her tendency to very jumpy and mouthy when overly excited.

Once you enter her circle of friends, Venus is a super sweet and loving girl. She enjoys cuddling with her people and will nudge for non-stop pets. She loves playing fetch and will bring the ball back each time so you can throw it again! She knows sit, down, paw, touch and is a master at “on your bed” which gives her structure and the direction to calm down when she gets too excited. She enjoys going for walks in quiet places and frequently checks in with her handler. 

Venus is slow to trust and will require someone who will continue to give her positive associations with people to help her grow and work through her stranger danger. She also requires structure and enrichment in her life so she can be the best version of herself. 

If you’re interested in being Venus’s fetch buddy, please fill out a survey today at  https://www.playersforpits.com/adoption-survey!

animal.description:
Because of the current situation with the COVID-19 (Corona) virus, in-person home visits are not possible at this time. Since this is a very important part of finding the best home for our dogs, we are not accepting any applications from first-time pet owners, applicants who have not had a pet in the past 3 years, or applicants who cannot furnish vet records. We hope you understand and that you will consider applying to adopt once restrictions have been lifted. Dante is approximately 10 years old, weighs 23 lbs and has a natural tail. He is partially blind but still has vision in his left eye. He gets eye drops 3 times daily which he does not like very well, but he can be bribed with treats. He has allergies and itchy skin so he is on Benadryl, special food and supplements. His coat has improved and is now nice and shiny. He does well with grooming. Dante loves to be outside and enjoys chasing squirrels, etc. Swimming has been encouraged, but he is not quite there yet. He is a barker, which we are trying to discourage with a special collar. He LOVES to go anywhere is the car. He will eat just about anything, but he likes to be left alone while eating. He is very sweet but can be skittish at times, which suggests that he may have been abused at some time in his past. He likes to sleep with his humans occasionally. He does well with adults and most other dogs but not sure about children or cats. This special boy is looking for his forever home. If you would like to meet Dante, please complete our adoption application and put his name at the top. http://dfwcockerrescue.org/ under Adoptions, Adoption Information.

For more pictures and information about this and all the cockers available at DFW Cocker Spaniel Rescue please visit our website at www.dfwcockerrescue.org

animal.description:
Thank you Artful Gardener!

'We have a soft spot for animals and Joyful Rescues here at The Artful Gardener! We're grateful to have held the Cabin Fever Party and Rescue Fundraiser before the shut-down happened and even more grateful that Joyful is able to continue its mission to save the lives of homeless pets. We have two (Lily and Toby) very special Joyful Alum in our household and it's impossible to imagine life without them! We know that these rescued pets will be well cared for until they're placed into the loving arms of their new families; that is why we're such big fans of Joyful Rescues! Thank you for saving these beautiful animals!
Thanks again for all you do!
Jean'

Magnolia was born around August 8, 2018 and weighs about 50 pounds. Magnolia is wonderful with all us humans and she would love another active, rough and tumble, dog in her next life. She is a rather rough player so the dog should be her size or larger and want to PLAY! We have found, as most Pointers, that she has too much interest in cats to live with any. We feel she will be fine with children old enough not to tumble easily. She is highly affectionate and loves to snuggle, but not until the play is done. She comes beautifully when called, but in a safely fenced/contained area as she is a Pointer mix and they usually have wanderlust. Magnolia is good in the car and does pretty well on leash.
This is all we know so far and we will be learning as we go and so will you!

The Adoption Fee for this dog is $350.00
Adoptions fees vary based on adoptability. In general our fees include spay/neuter, all age appropriate vaccines, Home Again micro-chipping & registration, worming & flea control - a 'complete' pet. We accept CASH or Visa/Mastercard ONLY. Joyful Rescues has no funding except for our adoption fees and miscellaneous donations. Pet care and vet bills are expensive - you must be ready to take on this financial (as well as emotional) responsibility. YOU MUST BE AT LEAST 25 YEARS OF AGE TO ADOPT A DOG FROM JOYFUL RESCUES We keep our pet list as up-to-date as possible. As soon as a pet is adopted, it is removed from the list. If a pet is still showing, it is still available for adoption. Can't Adopt Me? SPONSOR ME Look for the Link 'Special Instructions to Seller' if you want to note a particular pet

Before you seek to adopt a pet from Joyful Rescues, please read our Pet Adoption page http://www.joyfulrescues.org/pet_adoption.html.

Good with dogs: Yes, with proper intros
Good with cats: Unknown
Good with kids: No
Crate trained: Yes
House trained: Yes

Maxine is a remarkably smart girl that will make a loving and loyal companion for her future adopter(s). Her ideal home will be a stable, structured environment with a safe yard for energetic play. Maxine is an exceptionally athletic and eager playmate who will require a good throwing arm for her favorite pastime! She is a devoted dog who thrives under a caring, committed and confident master. Otherwise, she tends to be insecure, which manifests as reactivity toward strangers, unfamiliar dogs and surprise situations. Slow intros are a must with new dogs, and she needs time to warm up to unknown people. Maxine has had muzzle training to help ensure safety during initial encounters. Once she learns to trust and feels secure, she blossoms into a faithful and endearing pup! Maxine has made impressive progress over the past several months but will need continued guidance to reach her full potential and live her best life. With the right leadership, she will make a phenomenal addition to the right home and lucky adopter(s)!

Please Note: All dogs are posted until they are officially adopted. This dog may have other interested adopters in line. If you are interested in adopting, please fill out an application on our website at www.lasthopek9.org.

Questions? Please email adoptions@lasthopek9.org. For more photos, or information on upcoming adoption events where you can meet her, please go to www.lasthopek9.org or go to our Facebook page. Thank you for your interest in saving a life!

animal.description:
Meet Sumo. 
Sumo is approximately  5 years old & a svelte 50 lbs...on diet day. :)
This boy is an awesome dog who has not been appreciated the way he should’ve been. 
We would prefer somebody who has shepherd experience and understands a commitment to a dog, for better or worse through rich or poor times, for the lifetime of a dog… Not just during the pandemic. 

Sumo was adopted from a high kill shelter earlier this year and because of Covid they are moving and were not able to take him. They reached out on social media and a rescuer with a big heart who knew Sumo from the shelter said that he would help them out and brought Sumos story to a Rescuer with Mutts In Need

We are still getting to know Sumo but so far we know he is a low-key boy and prefers dogs that are not going to slobber all over him or try to be dominant. People are always asking us for dogs that can be by themselves and we hardly ever have them. Sumo is one that for sure can either be by himself or hang with a couple other dogs. He is such a good  boy.  We also know he enjoys affection,  getting baths and walks nice on a leash. 

Sumo loves to go for walks and hikes. He enjoys good food, soft ear rubs and a soft bed. He is house trained and ready for his forever home. 

 We would like to place him in a home that is low key and preferably no young kids.  This mellow boy has been through a lot and deserves a home where he can relax and just enjoy life.

If you have shepherd experience, or the very minimum large breed experience,  please fill out an application.

animal.description:
Wilbur 
"Staffie mix" by the shelter but seems more lab and bulldog mix
6-7 years old
Dog friendly (aka he ignores calm dogs, not impressed with hyper dogs in his face) 
Cat friendliness unknown
Will be fine with CALM kids 
Needs to lose weight 
Vetted but still needs neutered 
80lbs 

Rarely am I choked up reading a dogs story. Unfortunately I see horrible things all day, while they all affect me, I have learned how to compartmentalize in most situations. However every now and then a dog comes along that literally shakes me to my core. A dog that you read their story and look at their photos and/or video and have to remind yourself to breathe again. This dog did this to me, my eyes filled with tears and I couldn't comparmentalize it, I couldn't refocus and continue my day as planned. This is his brief story:

"Dawson came in today after being found hiding in the dog house of his yard. His "brother" had starved to death after their owner passed away in the house. We arent sure how long he had been gone, he had no friends or family around here. Dawson is SO SAD, he just lies in his kennel and wont get up. "

I cannot imagine the mental anguish he suffered watching his brother starve to death as food, at that time, was plentiful for him but his brother couldn't get to it. I cannot imagine the confusion and fear when his owner never came back and eventually he smelled the stench of decomposition. He retreated into his dog house when his food was gone, he was preparing for the same slow, agonizing death he watched his brother suffer. I cannot imagine the pain and toll this has taken on him, but my heart is shattered. 

Please welcome Wilbur (he doesnt know Dawson, and Wilbur just fits him) to High Plains PAW. I promise you will never be scared and suffering ever again. I promise we will get some of this weight off you so the rest of your time on this earth will be less physically painful. I promise that you are so extremely loved and I will spend every ounce of my being make sure you know that for the rest of your life. We cannot undo your suffering or erase your past, but we will focus on your future and make it more spectacular than you could even dare to imagine.

Also, PLEASE have a plan for your animals in case of your demise. This is sad on multiple levels, for the man who died and literally no one even knew he was gone, for the dogs, for everyone this has impacted. Please have a plan, part of responsible ownership and unconditional love is recognizing the need for future care for the animals.

WE DO NOT HAVE A FACILITY ALL OUR DOGS ARE LOCATED IN FOSTER HOMES. This means there is no place for you to go in person to view our dogs. We ask that an application be filled out and we will go from there!

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Juliet arrived in her Maryland foster home on September 19. Such a pretty name for such a pretty dog. Sadly her former life has left her emotionally scarred. She is distrustful of people, and painfully shy. At the shelter she snapped at people coming into her bubble. In her foster home she just cowers and doesn't take any joy in human interaction or being petted. At this time she stays on a 25 foot leash when she goes outside in the fenced yard, just so we can catch her and reel her back in. Thankfully she's fine with the other dogs and cats, and seems to thrive on a routine. We hope with some time she will come around and learn that people can be good and that petting and love are to be enjoyed, but she's not there yet. If she is to be adopted in the near future, she will need an adult only household and a very secure fenced area. She is a high flight risk.

Update 11/9/20, sadly Juliet shows only minimal improvement. During the day, we can let her outside with a reasonably good chance of coming in on her own. At night when we let her out, she must have the leash on. She does like a routine, and although I'm not sure you can call it "liking", but she seems to tolerate my elderly mother better than me, but she still does not show affection towards anyone and startles very easily. I wish I had a better update. Only time will tell if she'll improve.If you are an approved adopter and are interested in this dog, please let your case worker know. If you are not yet an approved adopter but are interested, please complete an adoption application!
You can review our adoption process, www.shenandoahrescue.org/adoption-process if interested. Donations can be made at shenandoahrescue.org/donate or on PayPal to info@shenandoahrescue.org

HOLLY is a friendly, 2-year-old (as of 8/30/20), 55-pound, Boxer and Hound mix.

She's sweet, social, and good-natured. A fine friend, this dog would be an outstanding addition to any family!

WHAT'S NEXT?

If you would like to meet, foster or adopt this pet, please fill out our online FOSTER/ADOPTION APPLICATION which can be found in the main menu of our website or at the bottom of this page - simply copy and paste the link into your browser. EASY PEASY!

Once we've reviewed your application, arrangements can be made for you guys to meet! It'll be kind of like a blind date!

***

This pet is spayed or neutered in accordance with our strict policy wherein all animals are altered prior to adoption. This pet is dewormed, current on vaccines, and started on monthly flea/tick and preventatives.

Animal Alliance's policy is that we will adopt dogs younger than 1 year old to families with children under 9 years old. We do not adopt dogs 1 year or older to families with children under 9 years old due to the unknown history of adult dogs. 

BY APPOINTMENT ONLY:  Meetings at our Adoption Center are by appointment only (no walk-ins).  An online adoption application is required and must be approved prior to meeting any animals.  Adoption appointments are set up by email by our Adoption Coordinator (no phone calls, please).  This process ensures our dedicated time to the animals in our care, as well as full attention to adopters at scheduled times.  

Prior to submitting an application, please see the Animal Alliance Adoption Process for adoption details.

To fill out an adoption application, go to:
https://www.animalalliancenj.org/fosteradoption-application/

animal.description:
Bleu Diamond has a short, beautiful ash-gray coat with white on her neck, chest, and tips of her feet. Her gray eyes are perfectly color-coordinated with her coat!
 Bleu Diamond is a happy little girl who is learning all about the joys of being a valued family member and navigating a new world! A bit shy at first when meeting new people, she will quickly show off her wiggly butt and happy face after a sniff or two. Bleu Diamond is more reserved around men, so she needs a few more minutes to warm up. She needs to be an only dog with an active family. This is a Velcro girl, who is most relaxed when she is around her people. 
Bleu Diamond is very curious and playful, and loves running after her toys and chewing on her bones and thick-braided ropes. She is looking for a home with a fenced-in backyard so she can zoom around and roll in the soft grass. Although she's energetic, when it's naptime, she is happy to curl up in her crate or on her blankets. Very eager to please and highly food-motivated, Bleu Diamond is making tremendous progress in her training. She is house-trained and crate-trained, knows Sit and Down, and is working on her leash training. There is so much to sniff and investigate and . . . um, including things on the kitchen counter!
Bleu Diamond will need her forever family to commit to building her confidence and transitioning into their world. She tells me she is looking forward to sharing some serious laptime as a pampered princess!
 Bleu Diamond's owners had to move and could not take her with them.
 Read more about Bleu Diamond on the Independent Animal Rescue website at https://animalrescue.net/dogs/d-20-141/.

animal.description:
Age: 3 years
Weight: 68lbs
Gender: Male
Energy Level: High
Overall Drive: Moderate 
Location: Bothell, WA

Gantu is playful, funny, affectionate, and very eager to please. Desperately loyal, he is very obedient and bonds very closely with his handler. If he were a human, he’d be a high-ranking police officer, strict and a rule-follower with good leadership qualities who is serious about protecting those around him.

Because he is still learning to trust those other than his handler, he takes a while to warm up to other humans. He will need a handler that can be patient with him and work with him through slow introductions to people both in and out of his home. Gantu has done well with other dogs, but because of his protective nature would be best matched with a neutral male dog or a female dog close to his size. He rides well in the car in his crate, is comfortable around loud noises, and he requires fair but firm correction. Gantu will require a handler who has Belgian Malinois experience who is committed to continuing his training and will be able to work with him through some of his more complex issues such as separation anxiety and destructive behavior. He is working on basic obedience and is fully crate trained. Gantu does not like water, so would do best in a home that isn’t interested in any water-based activities.

Gantu’s ideal home would be one with a breed-savvy handler who is committed to continuing his training, ensure controlled introductions to both people and other dogs, and who can be patient with him as he grows. He would do well in a calm home that offers opportunity for him to get controlled exercise.

WEST COAST ADOPTIONS ONLY

Must have previous or current, purebred Malinois experience OR other high drive working breed experience

Our adoption process includes- completion of an application, followed by a telephone interview. If that goes well, we will arrange for a home visit.
Adoption Fee: $500.00. Transport along Interstate 5 (Bakersfield, CA to Bellingham, WA) is available but cost not included in adoption fee. 

Please visit www.woofproject.org and fill out an adoption application located here https://www.woofproject.org/application

If you would like to meet any of our dogs please fill out an adoption application on www.maxxandme.org
Maxx & Me is an all volunteer, all foster home rescue and do not have a shelter. Please allow at least 48 hours for applications to be processed (missing information may slow the process, so please take your time and be thoughtful in your answers). All dogs posted are available (so no need to ask). We place dogs based on best home for each dog and not order of applications received. Lana has a very very heartbreaking a sad story. Someone contacted us via Facebook Messenger on a Thursday night, we rushed to her help ASAP. She looked to have been dragged by a car, all of her paws were very wounded and tore up. She was so scared, and intimidated by us but she let us help her. We cleaned her wounds as best we could and the next morning took her to the vet to get her checked out. Most of her toes were broken in her one paw, you could count every bone in her body. 

Lana is still at vet, she is being treated for her wounds, infections, and getting all the food and attention she wants. We are hoping to have her in our care soon, once she is healthy enough to leave the vet!!

Please help give this sweet girl a forever home of her own, that will love her unconditionally and treat her like a family member!

animal.description:
***PLEASE DO NOT CONTACT AUSTIN DOG RESCUE REGARDING THIS DOG. PLEASE CONTACT THE PERSON LISTED BELOW IN THE AD FOR MORE INFORMATION***

THIS IS A COURTESY LISTING. ADR is not responsible for the health, temperament, behavior or placement of this dog. Listings are done at the request of the dog's owner and as an outreach and community service in hopes of finding these dogs a loving, stable forever home. Placement decisions are made solely at the discretion of the owner and not Austin Dog Rescue. Owners are required to ask for an adoption fee from adopters.

This is the information that we received from Gulliver's current family:

Boris, our son and daughter-in-law’s dog, bit their toddler about 10 months ago. Prior to that incident, Boris had never shown any aggressive tendencies – ever. Ian had food in his hand, and was passing Boris in a tight space. No one had an actual visual of the incident- they just heard Boris give a quick growl and snap. Boris bit Ian’s jaw, which was snout level for Boris. The bite broke the skin, and was traumatic for everyone. The vet was contacted immediately after the incident, and said the best thing was to keep Boris and Ian in separate rooms. They had never existed in an environment of having Boris secluded; this was not a realistic or fair to Boris. Boris has been temporarily rehomed with our brother-in-law, Danny, while we continued searching for a new home. Danny fosters cats, and has officially adopted two geriatric cats, one of which is unable to jump up on a platform to eat cat food. Boris loves cat food, and Danny cannot keep Boris away from the cat food. Bottom line: Danny is committed to cats over dogs. 
Since COVID, I help care for our grandson, Ian, 3 afternoons a week. Our first priority is ensuring a safe environment for our grandchild; thus, we are unable to keep Boris. 

If you are interested in meeting this handsome fella', please contact Joseph at: joenorton15@gmail.com

animal.description:
Puppy shenanigans - everywhere, just puppy shenanigans. That is me, Bentley. I am an 8 month old puppy on the hunt for my people. I don't really have a solid story about where I came from, all I know is that one day, the luckiest day of my life, I became a Bella baby. I have grown up without much structure so I am really needing a human to set some boundaries and teach me my manners. I am not a bad little fella, just a pup that needs a little guidance. Let's just say I am wiggly, and goofy and am desperate to learn where my place is with a new family. Since no one has ever told me "no" or even took the time to teach me right from wrong, I got off on the wrong paw in my life start. Being in foster care has been wonderful. A life changer, my second chance. 

My new family should probably not have any little people or older people because I currently think it is okay to jump. Breaking that habit is a work in progress but for now, I might just knock over a little or an older friend. I have all this energy, puppy energy and I love to play and run. Older kids who would play and exercise me would actually be perfect or an active home with people who just want to include me in their life. Being around people is fabulous, so much better than being alone, I just need someone to believe in me and bring me home knowing that with their love, support and consistency I can be trained to be a very well mannered, bonded family member.

I LOVE going on walks and car rides are totally my jam. I love going places with my foster mom. She even taught me to "sit"! 

I really am a good boy, I have so much love to offer, I just need to control the goofy puppy that is still living inside me. I mean - look at me! Long legs, like legs for days (so we can walk together). I bet I would be a great running buddy if someone showed me what to do And my eyes. Great, big, beautiful brown eyes - you know you want these staring at you while you eat dinner (I heard that sharing is caring). And I am funny. A great big bundle of awkward fun. I am so ready to be yours. The sooner the better!
I'm very playful with the other dogs and I know sit and shake. 

You can change your life and mine and there is no better time to do that then now! I'm waiting, let's get forever started! 
If you would like to meet me, fill out an application and the Bella staff will arrange it. You can also meet me at the Bella adoption center where I am staying.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Mom was a Border Collie, Dad was a German ShepherdCaught you looking! My name is Brando. I am a sweet, loving, cuddle bug. I love to lay in my foster mom's lap and let her rub my tummy while I go to sleep. Sometimes, I will lay this way for hours. I know in a few months, I will be too big for laps, but for now, I love it. And my belly does need a good rub every day.
I am a puppy, I have very sharp puppy teeth. I am very eager to learn, but until I do, I am not a good match for small children who may get in the way of my mouth. My mom is a small Shepherd/Border collie, and my Dad was the neighbors German Shepherd who couldn't stay in his own yard. I am the last puppy from a litter of 6. I want to find my forever home too! I am loving and smart and will be your loyal companion for life. I am 90% house trained but I will have accidents in the house if I am busy and cant make it out side. I am too little to be 100% trained yet. So I am going to need some training. I will never be an outside dog. That just is not in my future. But, if you invest in my training, I will be the best dog ever! If you want the most gorgeous puppy you have ever seen, please fill out an application. I will be adopted quickly.
NOT APARTMENT APPROPRIATE, NO SMALL CHILDREN =========================================================
Please contact app@aarfhouston.org for more information about this dog. You can apply online by clicking on Application .
Puppies that are under 4 months old cannot be adopted outside of our Veterinary Service area. Please call for specific locations. Children under 8 years old often are not a good match for our puppies and dogs. In order to protect both, your child and our rescued dogs/puppies from harm, we seldom if ever adopt to families with young children.
Once your application is approved, we will schedule a meet and greet at one of our adoption events. Thank you for considering a rescue! The adoption fee includes vaccinations, Bordetella, de-worming, rabies, spay/neuter and microchip. There is a an additional $12.99 fee for Home Again for a lifetime registration of the microchip.
Puppies cannot be adopted outside of the Houston area until they are spay/neutered after they are 4 months old. It is against the law in the State of Texas for a rescue not to be sterilized so we have to make sure it gets completed and that we have record of it.
NOTE: In our bios, we provide information based on our volunteer's experience with a particular dog; such as temperament, training, and ability to get along with others.
AARF is a 501(c)3 Non Profit, all breed, no kill organization. Our group is always in need of donations in order to continue to give the needed medical care to our rescues. Adoption fees do not begin to cover all of the medical costs. Any donation , no matter how small is a big help and is greatly appreciated. Please help us to continue to help them. Thank you.

If you have ANY QUESTIONS or are truly interested in adopting any animal from PAW Animal Shelter Please, fillout an adoption application FIRST! WE are a high intake No Kill Shelter ran by a staff of 4 and do not always have time to answer every question asked by so many. If you are a good fit for the animal you are interested in -we will call to speak with you, If we feel you are not a good fit , we will contact you about other pets that may be a good fit for your home. Many people are losing the opportunity to adopt the animal they want because they fail to put in an application and the pet was adopted before we could answer your email. .If you have applied for an animal in our facility and have not received a response within 7 days, PLEASE call or contact us again. Though we do our best in trying to answer all emails in a timely manner, sometimes things get away from us, get lost or misplaced. It is never our intention to ignore a request about an adoptable animal in our facility.

Sandy Brown, Director, PAW Animal Shelter

animal.description:
Xena is a 4 year old, 92 pound rottweiler, probably a mix, but we'll go with rottie. She came to us as an owner surrender who could not manage the dog with her lifestyle.  We aren't sure what that means because Xena is a good girl.

Xena is probably best as an only dog because she is pretty dominant. If you want to know who in the dog kingdom wears the crown, it would be Xena. She is a very bossy girl and she just wants it the way she wants it. She can and does get along with other dogs, but the dogs needs to be low key and submissive. We'd prefer to just let her go to a home where she can be the Empress of all that She Surveys and who gets ALL the rotisserie chicken and not merely part of it. 

Xena is exceptionally social with people and she is very well-mannered. She is active and she is athletic which is typical for the breed. She needs a fenced yard with enough room to run because she occasionally feels the need for speed. This dog is housebroken and would not dream of peeing in the house because that is for the uncouth in her mind. She would be best in a home with kids past the age of 8 given her size and power. This is definitely a no cat dog. 

If you are interested in adopting this dog, please apply online, at https://bigfluffydogs.com/adopt/adoption-application/ and email corey@bigfluffydogs.com. 

Our main website, www.bigfluffydogs.com has more information about us and the rescue process. 

NOTE TO EMAILERS FROM PETFINDER: WE DO NOT RESPOND TO EMAIL INQUIRIES WITHOUT AN APPLICATION. WE REGRET WE CANNOT RESPOND TO EVERY EMAIL, BUT UNLESS YOU FILL OUT AN APPLICATION, WE DO NOT KNOW YOU EXIST. 

All known information about an individual dog is provided in its listing. We do our best to provide accurate information, but adopters should understand that each home is different and the dog may behave differently in a new home. Dogs are creatures of their environment and you help make the dog what it will be. Homes considering adopting a puppy must be prepared for 1.) Flexible schedules for potty training. Puppies can only hold it for one hour per month of age (i.e. a 4-month-old puppy can only go 4 hours without a potty break). 2.) Crate training until the puppy is at least one year old to prevent chewing on inappropriate things when you can't supervise. 3.) Socialization.  The more positive and varying experiences as a puppy the better, both in and out of your home. 4.) Puppy behavior and life stages are equivalent to a human toddler. It takes at least a full year to have a calmer, well-adjusted dog. Patience is required and when your dog's behavior is a positive experience for you and those around you, your patience will be rewarded ten-fold, for years to come.  Please do not consider adopting a puppy if you have not thoroughly thought through the pros and cons of having one. So many people end up returning them after 3-5 months because they didn't realize the amount of work involved in raising a puppy.  Patience, appropriate toys, socialization, and obedience training are all musts. All are time-consuming and can be expensive. All dogs require supervision with children and obedience training. Adopters that want to have good dogs must be prepared to put the time and effort into training a dog. Any dog requires work and effort, but a well trained, well-socialized dog is more than worth the effort to get them there.

animal.description:
Biskit| 3 years old | 27 lbs| Fostered in Trent Hills, ON

Hello my human friends, my name is Biskit, like a cookie, I am not a soft cookie, I tend to be a bit more hard, only because of my life history. I come to Canada from Saudi Arabia, In Saudia Arabia I was hit by a car during my life on the streets, please don't let the gait in my walk deter you from loving me. When I was hit by a car I had no one to help me so I had to heal on my own. I can't tell you how hard it is to heal your body when you have no food and water to nourish yourself with.

I was discovered by a caretaker who cleaned that restaurant nearby. Every day he would come find me and leave food by me, I couldn't move, I was petrified. Some humans would call it PTSD after being hit by a car, I am not sure about all of that, I just know that I was so petrified after, I trusted no one and was scared stiff, literally guys, I was too afraid to move. That Caretaker was my angel, for his generosity in feeding me, or I would have died for sure.
 
I was only a puppy when transferred here to Canada. Did I mention you Canadians are some of the friendliest people I've met? However I still arrived full of fear and lacked confidence & I didn't trust you guys yet, so of course there may be a bit of my nipping history, I am not proud of that. I worried every time someone came near me because I thought they wanted to hurt me.

Here's my happier chapter, I hope you enjoy hearing about it as much as I enjoy telling you about it.....I have spent the last few months within a doggie school with a live in trainer. Wow, she really has my heart, I can't tell you just how patient, loving and kind she was with me. No matter how many times I peed in the crate out of fear, or snarled at her, or hid in my crate, she would always wait patiently day after day until I finally came out of my crate and began to live the life I saw other dogs living. She will forever have a piece of my heart.

Thanks to her, I am a super trained boy.  I am happy to report that I have officially graduated doggie school with top A+ Grades. My instructor has taught me how to stay, sit, recall, to name a few. More importantly, my instructor is most proud  of how much I have come a long way from the frightened and insecure dog I once was.   

I am a work in progress still, as you humans call me "A diamond in a rough" I don't know what that means but it sounds cute, so I'll take it!! 
I am ready for a forever home with someone who can help me continue to thrive, here's what you should know:

I want to live in a rural community, I mean seriously folks, how do you want to live in all of that loud traffic and chaos of the city? NO THANKS!! I would require a backyard since I am very playful and enjoy a good run around! If you have children, I require them to be 13+ years old please. I am totally okay to live with another dog, if that dog is stable, calm and not unpredictable. Now, I don't mean to judge you, and I promise I am not, but you really need to have dog experience for me. I have worked so hard on my doggie training and resource guarding issues, if I go into a home, my human needs to be experienced enough to continue with the training my teacher taught me. Don't worry, my doggie school teacher will prepare you fully on what that entails. Easy Shmeezy!  

I know that I have had an extraordinary life, and I am lucky to be alive. I have waited SO long for a human who is going to take me into their lap and love me. Do you think that's you? I am eager to know more about you so please fill out the adoption application so we can make friends!! Make sure your home has balls, lots of balls and toys to chew on!! I don't want to sound spoiled but I really enjoy playtime!

animal.description:
WALLY ~1 year old. Good with older considerate children and dogs. Cautious with cats, does want to chase and play. Needs a companion animal.

GSRA adopts to residents of VA, NC, and SC only.

I am foxy boy with a lot of energy who wants to be part of your pack. I bark like a Shepherd and I am smart like a Shepherd and I have lots of cuteness going on!

Oh Yes I am totally a puppy. I love to play and be free to "zoom" around the yard. I play fetch and even bring the toy back to my foster mom or dad! I like all kinds of toys, squeaky toys, tug-of-war toys, tennis balls. But beware I love to chew on toys or bones or rawhides, so keep a supply of chew toys at the ready. If a chew toy is not around, beware that I can get a little mouthy with a soft touch, but I won't try to bite you. My foster parents are working with me to stop being mouthy, but don't forget I still have a lot of puppy in me.

I am pretty quick to learn. My foster mom & dad are working on my basic commands and I'm getting the hang of it when rewarded with a yummy treat. I'm also learning to walk better on leash. I am pulling less and learning to "heel", but not so much when I see a squirrel or deer.

If I meet you in the street, or in my foster home, I'll probably bark at you until I sniff you at my own term. After my sniffing is done, I'll then be happy when you pet me, but my foster parents are working on introducing me to people without a bark, or two. I am crate trained and will sleep in it at night but I also will sleep on a dog bed on the floor, or your bed if you let me.

So stock up on some toys and let me come into your home!

From Wally's Foster Parents:

Wally is very much a puppy because he wants to play most of the day, but he does take a couple of naps to build up his energy again. As with all dogs, his current high energy will dwindle as he gets older. Wally will give you many licks if you let him, but when he plays, he very lightly "mouths" and at times he runs full speed and could bump into you, for that reason we think that Wally would be a better fit without small children. We are working to lessen and stop the mouthing, but not there yet. Wally has played with a couple of other dogs in a friendly manner, but at times walking through the neighborhood he barks at other dogs with his hackles up. We are also working with him to keep walking, or to sit until another dog passes. We think Wally would be great with the right companion dog that would also help to drain some of his high energy.

Wally is housebroken and will sleep through the night. After looking at internet comparison photos, we believe that Wally is more of an Australian Cattle Dog, but still has some German Shepherd looks and of course smartness. He is a medium size dog and currently about 48 LBS which should be his top weight.

Wally currently goes on many walks during the day and is left off-leash in a fenced backyard that allows him to "zoom" and relieve some energy a few times a day. We would want to place Wally with a family who can let him run, or again play with a friendly or companion dog. Due to Wally's speed, we think he would be great at an "Agility" course if trained.

For more information on our adoptable pet list please visit: Adoptable Pet List

Please join us at our next Event(s):

Current Scheduled Events:

animal.description:
Georgia Is a two-year-old 48lb lab mix. Georgia is very shy with people but loves other dogs. She must go to a home with another friendly dog. She has a tendency to follow the other dogs leads on how to act with people. Georgia is a low shedder and is housetrained. She loves to go hiking and on trips to the beach with her favorite people who adopted her twin brother Heinz 57.  (You can see him in the picture) She also loves to swim. You can see her enjoyment with dogs and her jumps into the baby pool in the video below. 

Georgia and her brother came from the same hoarder situation as Blossom, Rambo & Kit. All of the dogs are awesome with other dogs but fearful of people they do not know. With the people they DO know they are awesome & extremely loving. They would all do best in a home with another dog, no kids & preferably someone who is familiar with shy and fearful dogs. 

To adopt Georgia you must have:
- another friendly dog
- 6ft fence and 
- preferably no kids. 
Please note that she does not dislike kids but this writer believes kids are loud, scary and leave gates & doors open. We really want Georgia to be adopted into the perfect environment as her brother was. 

If you meet the criteria above and would like to meet Georgia please fill out an application. https://www.muttsinneed.org/adoption-application.html

animal.description:
My name is CHICO and I'm a 4.5 yr M Brindle/White Beagle/Terrier Mix. I'm 22 lbs of PURE DAPPER DOG. I'm a nervous boy that was never exposed to much as a puppy and abused by neglect. As a result I'm very "guarded" and insecure and become "territorial and protective" When I first meet you, I'm shy and coy, but once I know and trust you...I'm right by your side. I need an EXPERIENCED dog handler who will go slow with me at first but be firm and give me daily structured exercise and discipline  to curb my insecurities. I'm a medium energy dog and would make a great jogging/biking/rollerblading partner. I'm cratetrained and housetrained  but could use a bit more work on leash training as I do pull a bit. I'm a bit of a resource guarder with my toys and my bed but not my food. My previous owners never worked with me on this but I can absolutely be trained out of this as I'm a SMART boy that is quick to learn and eager to please. I just need more interactivity and a "job" so that I don't get too "territorial" and protective. I'm ok with dogs in passing but because I'm not good with sharing things, it's best that I be a SOLO dog  with a SINGLE PERSON and unfortunately NO KIDS. I am FINE WITH CATS. I'm a little scared of them. Even though I'm from the city and used to all the traffic;  I would love a quiet home in the 'burbs with someone that can give me the structure, discipline, exercise & interactivity I need to be a fully balanced dog. IF you're up for the challenge.. I'm WELL WORTH THE EFFORT & promise to be your BFF!!

For more info/application - pls email: INFO@TAILSOFLOVERESCUE.ORG

animal.description:
Shoko! 

Meet Shoko, or “auspicious child”.  Why is he “auspicious”?  Because he is successful at stealing your heart!  Shoko is 100% sweetheart.  He is a senior, but he has a lot of life and spunk in him.  He loves going on walks (preferably in the grass because of his arthritis), getting head, back, and tummy rubs, going on car rides, getting treats, and taking naps on soft doggie beds.  He loves every dog he meets and his adorable curly tail starts wagging as he hangs out with his peeps.  Shoko would do best in a home that has a backyard that he can go out and enjoy and also provides opportunities to do his business.  He needs to go outside multiple times through the day, so he needs someone to be home with him most of the day, or at least only gone for a few hours at a time. 

 

He is quiet and only howls when he is excited to see you come home or sad you are leaving, otherwise he doesn’t make any noise.  He does have some arthritis and some pain, so that is managed with his medicine, soft beds, picking him up gently, and grassy walks.  He likes everyone he meets and is not afraid of anything, so he can handle a home that is calm or one that is more lively.  He does just fine with cats and birds and is a just a pretty chill dude.  He transitions to a new home quite easily and is a joy to have around.  

Are you looking for a handsome, sweet guy who will not only melt your heart, but will also get along with everyone?  Then, Shoko is your puggle.  He is a great ambassador for puggles, because he has the wonderful traits of both the beagle and the pug.  And that face…he is just too cute. CPR considers adoption applications from Florida Residents, Age 21 & over. Review our Application Process and Complete our Online Adoption Application at: http://www.compassionatepugrescue.com/adopt-surrender/

Sugar and Spice were discovered along a highway.  Very thin, dirty, & dehydrated.  Luckily it was an animal lover.  She spent some time gaining her trust and capturing her and the pup.  The looked for hours for any other pups.  She never found any and went back later with no luck.  We fear the worst if there were others.  We were contacted to help them.  Momma Sugar has turned into a very sweet and loving dog.  Now at around 43 lbs and fully vetted, she is ready to move onto a GOOD life where there is always proper care and love.  The last photo of her is her intake photo :-(  Approximate Date of Birth is 04/27/20

ALL DOGS ARE SPAYED/NEUTERED, UP TO DATE ON AGE APPROPRIATE VACCINATIONS, BORDATELLA, WORMED WITHIN THE LAST 6 MONTHS, AND MICROCHIPPED.  DOGS OVER THE AGE OF 9 MONTHS HAVE BEEN TESTED FOR HEARTWORMS, ANY OTHER KNOWN MEDICAL ISSUES TREATED OR NOTED. IN THIS LISTING.  

Contact should be made through email at dog_it_dig_it_rescue@yahoo.com OR texting to 812-264-7239.  We will be happy to answer your questions to the best of our ability.   We may not have an answer to your specific question.  The dogs in our care come from all kinds of situations.  Almost all of our volunteers hold full time jobs.  We receive a lot of emails and texts daily.  We do not have a shelter as most of our dogs are in foster care.  We do not have 'open' hours. IF YOU ARE UNABLE TO PRINT AND SCAN THE APPLICATION BACK, JUST TYPE ALL THE ANSWERS IN THE BODY OF AN EMAIL OR TEXT A PHOTO TO  812-264-7239.  Please be sure to answer ALL applicable questions.  We do attend, with the local shelters, the PetSmart Nationals events that are held about 5 times a year where you may view a lot of dogs from Multiple facilities at one time.
