animal.description:
Miska is 2-3 years old, 62 lbs. NEEDS TO BE ONLY DOG.

Hi my name is Miska, - that is Inuit for ‘Little Bear’.  I got the name because I am a female husky/ lab mix with beautiful blue eyes and the softest fur EVER!  My foster dad wanted to call me Cinnabon because I am soft and fluffy and colored just like a delicious cinnamon roll. I LOVE belly rubs and will pat you with my paw to encourage you to check out that soft fur in just the right place.   I am about 2 years old and am fully vetted and housetrained and very well behaved in the house. While I am crate trained, I do prefer stretching out on a cool floor on a hot day or on the sofa if I get the chance. The best thing is a sofa AND belly rubs. I would love to just hang out with you and snuggle up.  I generally walk well on a leash though I am still learning my manners when meeting up with other dogs. I like to bark at them and pull on my leash which I am learning is NOT the way to make friends and find a playmate. I really want to say hello and play but have this urge to show that I am top dog and the boss in our street.  I would love a home with a fenced yard to run and play in.  I am not scared of thunder or things that go bang in the night. I am treat motivated but it has to be the right treat at the time as I can be very picky about my food.

I understand basic commands and enjoy working for my preferred treats but my favorite is having ear and belly rubs or just hanging out.  I do LOVE car rides. Head to the garage and call me and I will be there hopping in with no problems. If I want something I will whine to get attention or come and swat you with my paw.  Let my fosters know if you would like more information or to come and see me. I am in Lake Wylie SC.

animal.description:
Audrey is a 3 yr. and 2  mo. old, spayed Staffy mix! She’s a thick girl and weighs 74 pounds! She is SO loving, wiggly, active, and sweet! She was recently brought back to SHS after being in a home for almost a year, where she was very much loved. But due to a lifestyle change, they had to give her up. 

She is at SEATTLE HUMANE SOCIETY so please contact them directly at  https://www.seattlehumane.org/. 

REPLIES TO THIS POSTING WILL NOT BE SEEN OR RESPONDED TO. 

Audrey has mellowed quite a bit in the last year, and has much better leash manners, greeting manners, and is all around more docile. She is still her happy, excited self, but doesn’t get nearly as rambunctious when she meets new people and dogs. 

She has had a variety of dog friends on campus, but we feel she needs to be the only pet in the home. While with us now, she’s seen dogs on leash and hasn’t been reactive. She has shown excitement, but not aggression, and she could have dog friends in the future with careful intros. 

She is so sweet, playful, loving and cuddly! She thinks she’s a lap dog sometimes and loves the water too! Audrey would do best with teens or older kids in the home too. Medically, Audrey is overweight and has hypothyroidism, so is on meds for that, along with some anti-anxiety meds to help with her shelter stress. 

Audrey really needs a chance!! 

She is at SEATTLE HUMANE SOCIETY so please contact them directly at  https://www.seattlehumane.org/. 

REPLIES TO THIS POSTING WILL NOT BE SEEN OR RESPONDED TO.

animal.description:
Note: Dogs are pack animals and do not do well away from other members of their pack. The adopter is the alpha member of the pack, and the dog or puppy needs as much one-on-one contact with the alpha as possible. For this reason, all Route 66 Rescue Inc. dogs are adopted to inside homes only. They must be on leash, or inside a secure fence when outside, and not left outside alone when no one is home. Invisible fencing does not qualify as protection since other animals and strangers have access to the dog. The dogs must be returned to Route 66 Rescue, Inc. if ever given up by the adopter. Thank you for understanding we want only the best for the dogs you give a forever home.

animal.description:
Cha Cha is a 2. 1/2 yr. old, spayed Cattle dog/Border Collie mix that weighs 44 pounds. She is super cute, perfect size and has the silliest sleeping positions! She came to SHS from a shelter down in Southern WA back in March 2020. She was brought in as a stray and was very shut down and scared but after a few days of staff working with her, she began to warm up! 

She is at SEATTLE HUMANE SOCIETY so please contact them directly at  https://www.seattlehumane.org/. 

REPLIES TO THIS POSTING WILL NOT BE SEEN OR RESPONDED TO. 

She has been in a variety of different foster homes where we have learned a lot about her. Cha Cha is fear reactive to new people and other dogs. She has a high prey drive for small animals such as rabbits, squirrels, birds, cats, etc. She is VERY smart and learns super quick, but needs someone that understands her breed along with able to continue working on her socialization to people. She dog tested fine at her previous shelter with other dogs and has done ok with some dogs that she’s met here, but she can be reactive on leash. 

Cha Cha needs to be the only dog in the home and will need secure fencing. She LOVES toys, and because she is so darn smart, training with toys as a motivator is a great an option for her! 

She is very sweet, loving and cuddly when she’s comfy and warms up to you! She loves to be on laps, couches, playing with toys, out exploring and chilling in backyards. She’d make a wonderful dog for someone who lives a bit more rural, has a fenced yard and no other pets. 

We think she’d best with teens or older kids in the home. Medically, Cha Cha is healthy, but she is an anxious dog, thus she is on some anti-anxiety meds. This girl is a smart cookie and just needs someone to give her a chance! 

She is at SEATTLE HUMANE SOCIETY so please contact them directly at  https://www.seattlehumane.org/. 

REPLIES TO THIS POSTING WILL NOT BE SEEN OR RESPONDED TO.

animal.description:
Meet Jack, the cutest little bear cub around! Jack is a 4 month old, grey, male, Newfoundland pup looking for a fresh start. Unfortunately due to irresponsible breeding, this cutie does show signs of possible neurological issues. He will be looking for a special home who can manage his needs and love him just the way he was intended to be. Little Jack is leash trained and trustworthy with free roam as he knows not to chew. He does bark to alert like any good boy would, and will dig if bored. Jack has never met a stranger and loves all people and animals. This playful boy will be further evaluated as to his medical needs, but just know you’ve never seen a more adorable punk in a doggie diaper! Jack does show an abnormal tail, has his own swagger of a gait, and is incontinent...but if you have experience with special needs pups, he’s your guy! He does not allow his uniqueness to stand in his way, and hopes his new family see all his potential as well! Could this fluff bucket be your next best friend?

animal.description:
Cecil – Pit Bull mix – 5yrs. – male (70 lbs.)
 
Meet our handsome boy, Cecil. Cecil was surrendered to a county shelter by his owner because the apartment manager found out he was there. This is such a sad story that we hear over and over. Poor Cecil didn’t do anything to deserve to lose his home, he was just born a pit bull. Luckily, we at SHR just LOVE pit bulls so we had to bring him back with us! Aside from being handsome, Cecil is sweet, polite, and knows some basic commands. He loves to lay in the baby pool at the shelter and will jump in and out throughout his play time. He’s good with other dogs, but isn’t super playful, he really just enjoys laying outside and getting attention from people. We believe he is housebroken because he has no accidents in his kennel. Cecil is loving, funny, and athletic... and just look at that smile! He is great company and will make a good companion during morning walks. Although he’s capable of hiking, he’d just as well cuddle on the sofa and spend time with his person watching TV. Cecil is everything you could ask for in a 70-pound package! If our sweet boy sounds like a good fit for your life, please fill out an application to get things started.

animal.description:
Quick Stats
* Spayed ~70 pound Female; DOB 2019
* House & Crate Trained
* Current on Vaccinations; Microchipped 
* Heartworm positive, slow-kill treatment started
* Loves people, but not tested with children
* Not fond of other dogs and cats, probably best as only dog
* Needs experienced owner

Lovely girl Ada is taking applications for her forever home. Ada is house and crate trained, although she would rather not be crated. So far no accidents. We are working on leash manners and commands.

Ada needs an owner she can respect. In addition, she seems to have not been around other dogs. She’s fine with people, but doesn’t know how to react to with dogs, so becomes anxious, which may seem aggressive to other dogs. She does however have one best friend, Xena, who has gotten her to play and socialize. They chase each other around the yard and have a great time. She tries to act like she doesn’t like her, but her tail wags and she looks delighted. So with proper introduction and work, she might be OK with another dog of the right temperament.

Ada is heartworm positive. We have started the slow-kill treatment for her, which is probably the best for her, given her high energy level and young age. We will send all medications and directions with her.

If you think this lovely young lady would fit into your home please fill out an application. 

Link to Application:
http://www.gsdrescuectx.com/adoption-application.html

animal.description:
*COURTESY POST DISCLAIMER: This dog is a courtesy post and is not affiliated with Friends to the Forlorn (FTTF). FTTF is not liable for this dog and an adoption of this dog would be independent of FTTF. All courtesy posts are spayed/neutered.
Breed: Pit Bull TerrierGender: FemaleEstimated Date of Birth: January 2, 2012Size: 60 lbsLocation: Atlanta, GA
Adoption Fee: $150
Bella is an incredibly loving, sensitive, and attentive companion. She really wants nothing more than to please and is super engaged when challenged with new tricks. She's very food motivated and highly trainable, so much so that she would likely be successful and have a great time with agility training.
Although Bella is 8 years old, she is still very playful and active; she's really just a puppy at heart. She is extremely curious, loves to sniff around, play tug, and (for some reason), jump up on any wall she sees. She hasn't quite mastered fetch just yet, but she would love you to teach her! She is content to roll around in the grass and explore new areas, but at home, she's a an excellent snuggle-bug as she loves to cuddle and be close to her person. Bella is a pretty mellow lady, but is really up for anything - she's ready to relax with you or zoom around the yard. Her pittie head-tilt is one for the record books and will melt the heart of any onlooker. She has some really hilarious sleeping positions and often smiles in her sleep.
All around, Bella is an amazing dog and would make a wonderful addition to a family where she can be the only pet. She has some fear-based reactivity that doesn't make her the best candidate for a stroll in a city park, but she would love a fenced yard to call her own and people she can bond with.
*Friends to the Forlorn is assisting in the placement of Bella. If you are interested in adopting this boy, please contact us for more information!
animal.name: Bella - Courtesy Post

animal.description: Sitting pretty for her glam shots, sweet Fiona is as loveable as she is lovely.  This one and half year old Pit Bull mix is a friend to all and very affectionate.  She was surrendered after her owner moved and could no longer provide a suitable home.  Fiona is a young healthy dog that likes to have fun and needs a fenced in yard with room to run around.  She would love to have a family that will take her on walks and play games with her.  She’s a solid fifty three pounds of muscle too.  Fiona is a good match for someone who enjoys a full active lifestyle and has the time to spend with her.  She would love to go running with you or go hike in the park.  She loves children but it would be best if they were older because of her large size.  Amiable and outgoing, Fiona does well with other dogs that enjoy rough and tumble play.  She would also be perfectly content as the only dog in the home.  Fiona is big on hugging and wants to be near you.  She craves companionship but is not overly needy.  She will entertain herself with toys or chew bones if you’re too busy to play.  Fiona prefers to do her business on grass but will need some supervision when she first comes home.  It won’t take her long to adapt if you keep to a consistent schedule.  Fiona is eager to please and very responsive to praise; especially if she gets a treat!  She is a devoted dog with a huge heart and so much love to give.  Come see for yourself!  To adopt this pet, Click "More About Us" and then "Adoption Application" to be directed to our online HSNWGA application form.  You will be contacted by our Adoption Coordinator once your application is reviewed and approved.  Due to high volume of applications, we are only able to contact those applicants that best meet the needs of that individual pet.

If you are interested in adopting this dog, please download and complete an Adoption Questionnaire from our website and email Liz at elizabethg@k-9lifesavers.org
You can learn about the adoption process and find a Word, PDF and ONLINE version of the questionnaire by visiting: http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/howtoadopt/.
Dog's Name: Koda
Estimated Breed : Lab/Bulldog Mix
Approximate Age: 1-2 years
Approximate Weight: approx. 54 lbs
Currently Living at: Boarding
Adoption Fee: $300
DOG'S DESCRIPTION
Koda is a sweetheart with a striking orange coat of fur. He is in the kennel hoping that he will be the next to find his forever home and family. He is very strong so no young children, he may knock them down. Koda will do best as an only dog and would love a home with a fenced yard to run in.
Your new pet will require a refresher in house-training. K-9 Lifesavers strongly recommends all new adopters enroll their new pet into obedience training. This provides for an easier transition into a new home, ensures the dog remains well socialized, and helps form a bond between the dog and the new family.
Adoption fees cover basic vetting, spay/neuter surgery (for dogs over 6 months old), rabies, distemper/parvo vaccinations, treatment for worms, heartworm testing, monthly heartworm prevention and monthly flea/tick prevention (while the animal is in our care), and transport costs from high-kill shelter. Please note that on average, K-9 Lifesavers spend significantly more on each dog than their adoption fee. Adoption fee for HW positive dog also covers heartworm treatment at our partner vets.
Foster Program: Foster homes provide for the temporary care of a rescue until the dog is placed into a loving, forever home. For more information on becoming a foster parent, and our Foster Program, visit http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/foster/ or email our Foster Coordinator at foster@k-9lifesavers.org
Sponsor Me! Make a tax-deductible donation today by visiting us at http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/donate/ . Donations help us offset boarding costs and additional medical treatment for those dogs who need it. K-9 Lifesavers receives NO federal funding and survive with your generous support!
For more information on K-9 Lifesavers, or to view a complete listing of all our Adoptable Dogs, visit our website at www.k-9lifesavers.org.
Please "like" our Facebook Page for the most current events and new dogs.
Thank you for considering a rescue dog!

animal.description:
Vince Vaughn is a 3 to 5 year old lab pointer mix. This guy is definitely large and in charge. He's one of our more challenging dogs. He's not a fan of getting a physical exam and had to be muzzled for a routine vaccinations and heartworm test. He's quite happy and charming around people when he doesn't have to do anything that he doesn't want to do, but if pushed, will growl and become a bit of a handful. Vince needs a very dog savvy owner who is willing to provide the necessary training and behavioral rehabilitation to make him a good addition to their house. He does get along with other dogs as long as they tend to be submissive to him. We know there's a home out there for events, but we need to make sure it's the right one for him and his new family. Based on the behavioral concerns, we are recommending a home with no children younger than 16 years of age. Dogs are generally tested with dogs of their own size; and dog meets with the resident dogs are always encouraged. Our cat test should be used as a general purpose screening only to rule out overt aggression; we always recommend caution when introducing dogs to cats in the home. Recommendation on suitability of placement with children by their ages is based on behavioral observations including energy level and response to body handling. We never recommend leaving young children unsupervised with dogs, and we cannot guarantee the behavior of dogs with children, other pets or cats. Behavior evaluations should be considered as a snapshot of the behavior of the dog at this point in time; SCPR believes all dog families need to be prepared to invest time and energy into training as well as provide common sense management of their new dog. We always encourage family to do some research on the breeds or mixes of breeds prior to adoption as many can have some unique characteristics that may or may not fit into their families. For more information about this dog or any others at our Shelter, please visit www.doitforthedogs.com. We are the Second Chance Pet Rescue in Grove, OK. 918-786-7630. You can email us at doitorthepets@gmail.com

animal.description:
Our handsome tripawd boy Dale is ready to find his forever people! He's a big sweetheart who has a playful spirit and young dog enthusiasm. Dale came to us with a front leg that was mangled from an old injury that hadn't healed correctly. The vet advised amputation and he adapted quickly to having three legs, since he hadn't really been relying on his injured leg for some time. He gets around quite well and can even go up and down stairs, but he does tire out fairly easily, especially in the heat. He'd love to have his own fenced-in yard where he could run around with a toy and then plop down in the shade, next to his person, and watch the dragonflies buzz by. 

Dale is a lovebug who thinks he is a lap dog, he's got some puppy energy and doesn't always know his own size, so his perfect family would be with adults or older children. We'd like to find him a home without other pets. While he enjoyed playing with dogs in the past, he lost a bit of confidence in his interactions post-surgery, and he's working on some training to get back on track. Dale is really ready to flourish and just wants a stable home with a family that will support him and help him become his best self! If you are ready to be Dale's hero and discover what a lovable pup he is for yourself, fill out our pre-adoption application at https://oneloveanimalrescue.com/pre-adoption-application/ and we'll introduce you!

animal.description:
** FOSTER NEEDED: CURRENT FOSTER HAS GIVEN US TILL FIRST OF MARCH TO F IND A NEW SPOT FOR HER. NO PLACE TO GO AND WE NEED COMMITMENT UNTIL WE GET THE RIGHT ADOPTER. TEMP FOSTER PUTS A DOG I JEOPARDY. WE CANNOT SLAP DASH PLACE A DOG OR MANUFACTURE AN ADOPTER. WE MATCH DOGS WITH ADOPTERS. HAPPY IS A LEASH PULLER AND SHE IS NOT GOOD WITH OTHER DOGS BUT A LOVE OF A COMPANION DOG WITH HER PEOPLE AND LOVES KIDS

IF THIS GIRL appeals to you please go to our website and fill out our online adopt app. There is no obligation to adopt if she isn't the right match but this is where we should start to find that out. ALso See her videos on our FB page.  

STATS: Happy is about a year and a half spayed female teenage puppy. She is a Koolie X ACD (Heeler) X Catahoula mix. Up to date on vaccs, HW tested and Negative, on Heartguard monthly prevention. On topical Frontline tick and flea meds. Weighs 44.6 pounds. She is a leash puller but she has toned it down a lot. Loves the water, and even obsessed with. She is a bit wild with car travel but has improved. Remember she is still very much a tri working breed puppy that is full of herself. She wants to go after anything moving, it often a game. She is needing slow introductions with strangers handling her like at the vets office. So for the sake of time constraints and safety they muzzled her for a brief period on her last vet visit. She did ok with the muzzle and the foster home has a muzzle they use only when absolutely necessary, mostly in trying to improve dog interaction. Crate broke to open wire crate. She is so good with ball playing and she is so fun and loves it and kids play fetch with her. The foster family introduces her to strangers by letting them play ball with her after the initial slow introduction and her warming up a bit to them. Like most working breeds, she is one family one pack oriented. Microchipped  She is a very vocal dog. She is happy, hence her name. She is respectful in the home and she listens and then remembers. Takes correction well. She needs a strong leader not a boss. Someone she can trust that has confidence. She does not beg for food at the table. All her issues are social, not stubbornness or unwillingness or testy. Very respectful in the home. She is a very needy dog for her pack social interaction so she is a good companion dog and family dog in the making. 
HISTORY: She was a stray to begin with. She was a puppy in a home that was not suitable for her, had little socialization and then a good Sam took her in and the husband wasn’t happy because he wasn’t consulted so she to go and came into rescue. They tried her with other dogs and another owner and it didn’t pan out, it wasn’t done properly but they didn’t know that. They did their best. Then she went to a foster for rescue and the foster used shocking devices on her after being told it was not acceptable. She was then moved to another foster and they have done an awesome job turning some things around. The shocking device left burn marks on her neck but those have healed. However, it did its work as usual and we see the problems because dogs remember when they have been hut. The result of shock collar use is still being dealt with as far as behavior issues and she needs more time and patience to work through that and the fact that she is 3 working breeds adds to the mix. The reason she isn’t being adopted by the current fosters is because they have dogs she doesn’t get along with, (also part of the shock collar residuals, also they have a lot of company and with fires and with Covid and such, it is just pretty impossible for it to work well for them to keep her. They have done an amazing job so far with helping her along)   

GOOD: Loves to play ball. She loves kids but she is large and puppy awkward and wild at times. Absolutely zero aggression with kids. Loves them. She is extremely affectionate and she can’t get enough love and be close enough to you. Once she gets acquainted she is very cuddly and affectionate. Loves the water. Very smart and eager to please, very trainable, extremely food motivated and rewards with affection and ball too, so easy to teach tricks and agility in a back yard. She has no interest in going off to play she won’t run away or bolt, she just wants to be with her people. She is not a very independent dog, she is Velcro dog. 

BAD: She is people cautious like most working breeds. She is manageable with caution and slow introductions. Fosters are careful with introductions. She is less friendly or slow to get acquainted with men over women. Tall people also are a bit of a trigger but manageable. She is pack protective and that is not uncommon with working breeds but adopters need to be aware of it. Her senses as to what is a threat is not clear. She is a baby and a teenager pup and no socialization properly so she still needs work on her judgements. She probably needs more exercise right now as well. More exercise seems to tone her down. She is moderately food possessive but gaining on it (ADMIN NOTE: We in rescue know how to work on that and can progress that and even get beyond that and will give help to a new adopter if needed). She is stimulated by cars passing the car she is riding in, and bike riders, runners: Mostly she barks and it is a mix of excitement and being protective. Normal for 3 working breeds in one dog and puppy. We see it often. 

UGLY: She does not like dogs period. Her prey drive is high so no small critters whatsoever for her in her new home. This will be the biggest challenge. It has been tested and this is absolute for her success in a new home. She must be accepted as she is with these limitations.

home_environment_attributes.other_animals: We say none because she is so dog reactive and cat prey driven.

animal.description:
Tucker is a 6 year old double Merle Aussie. He was born blind and deaf but full of love and that smart Aussie spirit! Tuck was surrendered by his owner through no fault of his own in August 2020 and has been fostered in Michigan since then. It’s hard to call Tucker disabled because he does such an amazing job navigating his surroundings but he certainly is special! He has an amazing sense of smell that can alert him to visitors up to 100 yards away (observed by his foster mom) and he insists on meeting those visitors promptly with a sniff. He loves everyone and will hop when especially excited to greet people. Interestingly, it’s been noted by his foster parents, that Tucker gets very excited when meeting humans who also have special needs such as a foster uncle with intellectual disabilities and a family friend with physical disabilities. 

Tucker is very easy to fall in love with but in the beginning he can be tricky to live with. For that reason he needs a home and family that are ready to make a commitment to him with the understanding that the first several weeks may be rocky. This may mean making changes to what the humans are used to in order to be flexible for Tucker. When he is adjusting to new surroundings he can be very vocal and this has caused him to be returned by potential adopters. A deaf blind dog can easily get their days and nights mixed up and due to their limited senses are very sensitive to change. He thrives on routine having a specific bed and bedtime routine and activity during the day. He is used to being kenneled when humans are gone but will not tolerate being locked in the kennel once you are home. When Tucker is unsettled he barks, a lot. His endurance in barking should not be underestimated and should be prepared for until he settles and adjusts. He is great with cats and loves other dogs however he does not follow the other dogs cues and this has often led to them becoming aggressive with Tucker. It’s recommended he is the only dog or with another that is very accepting, laid back and patient. Tucker can walk on a leash when he’s in the mood to but for routine potty breaks and exercise he requires a fenced in area. He is happiest having free roam of the house during the day when humans are home and will not tolerate being limited to one room. He can manage stairs and is trained via mats for texture and knows several tap signals. 

His nose and love of extra food (he’s a big boy weighing in at about 85 pounds) can get him into mischief like opening cabinets with his teeth when seeking an extra treat! His hobbies include running circles when he’s bored and occupying the couch with or without the humans to snuggle, but he’d prefer with. Tucker can be a lot of work but every ounce you put into him he will give back in love and companionship over time. He will be a faithful and diligent guard (that nose again)! for the right home. 

 If you think Tucker is a good fit for you, please fill out our application:
https://www.australianshepherdsfurever.org/adoption-application

animal.description:
Heeyy! My name is Lady Bird but everyone calls me Bird. I'm a 3 years young
female, 55 lbs, Doberman Pinscher/Hound mix
and LOVE people. Like I seriously love people no matter their size. I'm such a good girl! I know to go potty outside and I even walk pretty well on the leash if I do say so myself. I'm also crate trained but I'd honestly rather lounge on the couch while you're gone. I get awfully jealous of other animals so prefer to be pampered solo and be an only child smothered with love and toys! It may sound a bit conceded but I have the best personality and love to talk to you with my little howls. People call be goofy but I think charismatic is a nicer way to put it.
To adopt me, please apply at www.hhfrescue.org.
The adoption fee includes vaccinations, bordetella, deworming, rabies, spay/neuter, microchip, a lifetime registration of the microchip, and sales tax. If adopting a puppy, the rabies and spay/neuter will be done at the same time by our vet once they are 4 months old and billed to us. It is against the law in the State of Texas for a rescue not to be sterilized so we have to make sure it gets completed and that we have record of it.

The address for our rescue center is 34 County Road 2266, Brundidge, AL 36010. We are one turn off Hwy 167. No appointment necessary for pets that are located at the rescue center. Appointments must be made to visit pets in foster homes. Appointments can be made by calling 334-508-2367 or emailing troyanimalrescueproject@gmail.com. Location information will be listed beside the pets name if they are at a location other than our rescue center.

Questions can be emailed to troyanimalrescueproject@gmail.com or call 334-508-2367.

Shilling and Sixpence are an almost 8 year old bonded sister and brother pair that have lived together since birth. Ideally, they would be placed together in a home that can give this energetic duo plenty of exercise! They need some leash work, but know sit, down, and no. They also seem to be housebroken. Their former owner said they don't care for smaller dogs, especially ones that might be too "in their face." They currently are living with a larger hound mix and a Chihuahua/terrier mix and have done well with both of their foster siblings. Shilling loves squeaky toys, and will happily rip one to shreds in her dog bed. Her brother, Six, is more laid back and submissive. Per their prior owner, they have done fine with cats, but in their foster home, they did intensely bark and corner the cat. Homes with cats would likely need to be evaluated on a case by case basis, as any cats would likely need to be larger and "dog-savvy." Both terriers are altered, up to date on vaccines, and heartworm negative.

Www.russellrescue.com/adoption

animal.description:
"All I want for Christmas is a Home!"
Snicker has a brother, Doodle, that found his forever home for Christmas.  Snicker is about 6 months old and may have a little Min Pin or Dachshund in his genes and weighs 15 lbs. He and his brother were saved from Mexico. Snicker knows basic commands of sit, come, shake, and he knows how to use a doggy door. If you are looking for a "lap dog" this is your guy! He loves to snuggle and will curl up beside you on the couch/chair and fall fast asleep.

Filling out an application is the first step in the adoption process. If you have questions, the best way to contact us is to email azdesertrottis@aol.com.

We don't always bring all animals to our adoption events so check ahead of time to make sure the animal you are interested in is still available. Some animals listed may already be promised.

Arizona Desert Rottie & Pals Rescue is a NO KILL rescue serving Tucson and the surrounding area. 

A home visit is usually required for the safety of our animals. We check the yard to make sure this little pup cannot escape, no predator can get in, and also look for hazardous plants. 

We do not adopt our dogs out unless you have a secure, fenced yard, it’s a requirement for the safety of the dog. At the end of the application, please include the type of fencing and the height of the fence you have around your yard. 

If you're interested in Snicker or any of our dogs, please fill out a pre application at: http://www.azdesertrotti.com/html/to_adopt.htm
Once you have filled out the pre-adoption application, someone will contact you about the dog to answer your questions and tell you where our Sunday adoption event is held.

Our dogs are bathed, dewormed, vet checked, given their required shots, spayed or neutered, and microchipped. 

Our rescues are homed with foster parents. They are fostered in homes so that we can tell you a little bit about their personalities, feeding schedule, habits, behavior, whether they get along with other dogs. We can tell you if they are crate trained, if they are leash trained and house trained. Most dogs need a refresher course on potty training when they go to a new home. They need to learn your routine, and it will be up to you to teach them. 

Even the most abused animals can be wonderful pets. It takes patience, love and good food, along with fun and commitment to the animal. Fosters work with these animals. They are a part of our families, while we are lucky enough to have them.

After you get home from work or a long outing, she’ll be at the back door waiting for you with a howl and lots of tail wags. She’ll hate getting out of bed in the mornings as much as you do, and keep you company in the office while you work remotely. She’s very good at reading the room, whether you’re in need of a laugh, a friend, or a comforting snuggle. She knows ‘Sit,’ ‘Lay Down,’ ‘Shake,’ ‘High Five,’ ‘Off,’ ‘Place,’ and ‘Bang.’ She is leash/collar trained and does fine in a kennel. 

Ripley is a wonderful dog in need of a great home. 

She is approx 2 years old, 60 lbs and heartworm negative. Ripley prefers to be the only pet with older children.

If you are interested in any of the dogs available at New Leash Rescue, you can reach out to the foster listed below for more information and then complete an adoption application which can be found at https://www.newleashrescue.org/adopt/policy.  Please email the completed application to newleashrescue2018@gmail.com

Claudia is a pretty mellow girl.  Around 8 years old.  She loves to take a nap after breakfast in the warm sun!  She gets along well with her 5 furmates.  Not totally house broke but is learning to use pee pads.  She prefers to sleep under the covers on the bed!

Claudia has undergone treatment for heartworm and is ready for her own home!  Her new home needs to commit to year round heartworm preventatives for the rest of her life due to her treatment.   This will cost around $8 dollars per month.   

During her heartworm treatment we have been watching Claudia's lungs, and xrays that were just done and sent to a radiologist show that her lungs have improved from the last time we did xrays.  She is currently on doxycycline and will likely have a slight cough for the next few weeks up to a few months as her lungs continue to heal.   Claudia's adopter needs to be willing to continue on with any follow up needed on this.  

Claudia is spayed and had a recent dental, she is up to date on vaccinations, microchipped,  and current on preventatives. 

Adoption fee is $350 + tax (no checks) 

Foster to contact: Tami  @    tami.reed1227@gmail.com


Our fosters do the best they can to provide all information about the animal's background and temperament while in foster care in their home. An adopters routine and home environment is likely going to be different than that in their foster home. 

Sometimes there is more that comes out about a dog's personality once they have been able to settle in a home and truly become comfortable. There are great articles out there written about the different stages a pet goes through after adoption, discussing transitions that happen at 3 days, 3 weeks, and 3 months. We highly recommend reading about this - it will help you understand the transition your new pet goes through.

animal.description:
Zinger arrived at Horse Creek Wildlife on May 26, 2020.

Zinger is a striking Labrador Retriever/Hound mix with tons of energy!! He loves running and romping with other dogs in our fenced exercise areas.  He never meets a stranger and enjoys going for leash walks with our volunteers.

He is full-grown weighing 44 pounds.

Zinger is a great dog and promises years of love and friendship! Do you have room in your home, heart and life for this big lovebug?

All of our dogs are spayed or neutered and are current on all vaccinations. They are on monthly heartworm and flea/tick prevention. All of their medical needs are taken care of before they are available for adoption. Our adoption fee is only $100.00. Please complete an application, if you have found a dog you are interested in adopting. You can find our application at www.horsecreekwildlife.org/applic.html. Once completed, you can forward it to adoptions@horsecreekwildlife.org or fax it to 731-926-3000. Kim Austin, our adoption facilitator, will be in contact with you as soon as she has an opportunity to review your application. Understand that she has other duties and she will not ignore any interest shown in adopting one of our dogs. An application will need to be approved before a scheduled time to visit our dogs will be set up.  It may take up to 48 hours before she returns your call or responds to your email, due to work schedules, holidays and adoption events. We do the very best we can for the dogs we have rescued and do not take the adoption process lightly. Please be patient and understand that we will place our rescued dogs in the very best homes possible and reserve the right to refuse applications.

animal.description:
Peanutbuddie is a handsome, muscular, 3 year old, hound mix and is known as Buddie by his friends.

He weighs 62 pounds. Inside the home, he shines as an obedient, very intelligent, clean, loyal, respectful, loving dog that is crate trained.

Peanutbuddie is very alert outside the house, focusing on sights and sounds of prey.

He will go to great lengths to obtain his target, so he needs a high fence of at least 6 feet. He is playful, energetic, tracking prey and enjoys challenging games, his toys and running.

Peanutbuddie is relaxed with those he has observed for several days, but looks constantly for cues in those he doesn't know yet, sometimes misreading their intentions. So, it is best if he is not placed in a home with children or in settings with active newcomers.

Peanutbuddie has good potential for a rural area or fenced in large area where he is free to guard his domain from critters that enter. He enjoys using his incredible smell and sight, and the outside stimulates his imagination.

His foster family sees that he can be aggressive with cats. Neighborhood children walking their dogs nearby may overly excite him.

For inquiries, email inquiry@angelsrescue.org

An Adoption Application for this dog can be found and submitted online at http://www.angelsrescue.org/adopt/adoption-forms

Please be sure to like our Facebook page https://www.facebook.com/angelsrescue.

*Some of our animals receive a high volume of applications, and we strive to select the best home for each animal. However, we have many wonderful homeless pets available.

animal.description:
Patsy is a pretty, spunky 18 mo. old terrier mix.  She weighs about 15 lbs.  She is a typical smart, eager terrier and is learning all the things she needs to know to be a great companion!  She's dog selective, but will do best in a home with a compatible playful, confident canine companion.  She's OK with dog-savvy cats.  She still has a lot of nervous energy, but is learning to channel it into playing with her dog friends, going for walks, snooping around outside, etc  She's housetrained, crate trained, and leash trained.  She will do best with a terrier-savvy person with rescue dog experience who'll be able to continue her training and socialization.  She's an active dog and would not be good in a home with small children or anyone unstable on their feet.  Patsy's adoption fee is $300.  LOCAL ADOPTION ONLY.

This dog may be at one of the Prescott pet stores on Sat. If you're interested, please call in advance to confirm that we're bringing this dog and where we'll be. Call for more info. 928 708-0799.
